{"title_page": "Swiftstudent", "text_new": "'''SwiftStudent''' is an online tool with information and template letters for users to appeal their [[College financial aid|financial aid packages]] at US colleges and universities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Douglas-Gabriel |first1=Danielle |title=As colleges brace for financial aid appeals, there\u2019s a new tool to help students file them |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/04/15/colleges-brace-financial-aid-appeals-theres-new-tool-help-students-file-them/ |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wan |first1=Tony |title=Students Need More Financial Aid Than What They Applied for. A Free New Tool Can Help. |url=https://www.edsurge.com/news/2020-04-15-students-need-more-financial-aid-than-what-they-applied-for-a-free-new-tool-can-help |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=EdSurge |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The tool is available free of cost and was released by [https://shs.foundation Seldin/Haring-Smith Foundation] and the company [https://formswift.com FormSwift] on April 15, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=St. Amour |first1=Madeleine |title=New Tool for Financial Aid Appeals |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2020/04/16/new-tool-financial-aid-appeals |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=InsideHigherEd |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hoover |first1=Eric |title=Financial-Aid Appeals Are Mysterious. This Tool Was Built to Simplify Them. |url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Financial-Aid-Appeals-Are/248528 |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=The Chronicle of Higher Eduction |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stratford |first1=Michael |title=New website launches to help college students appeal financial aid decisions |url=https://login.politicopro.com/?redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fsubscriber.politicopro.com%2Farticle%2F2020%2F04%2Fnew-website-launches-to-help-college-students-appeal-financial-aid-decisions-3979337 |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=Politico Pro |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kreighbaum |first1=Andrew |title=Colleges Brace for Student Aid Appeals as Virus Slashes Incomes |url=https://about.bgov.com/news/colleges-brace-for-student-aid-appeals-as-virus-slashes-incomes/ |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=Bloomberg Government |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|https://formswift.com/swift-student/}}\n", "text_old": "'''SwiftStudent''' is an online tool with information and template letters for users to appeal their [[College financial aid|financial aid packages]] at US colleges and universities.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Douglas-Gabriel |first1=Danielle |title=As colleges brace for financial aid appeals, there\u2019s a new tool to help students file them |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/education/2020/04/15/colleges-brace-financial-aid-appeals-theres-new-tool-help-students-file-them/ |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=The Washington Post |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Wan |first1=Tony |title=Students Need More Financial Aid Than What They Applied for. A Free New Tool Can Help. |url=https://www.edsurge.com/news/2020-04-15-students-need-more-financial-aid-than-what-they-applied-for-a-free-new-tool-can-help |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=EdSurge |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The tool is available free of cost and was released by Seldin/Haring-Smith Foundation and the company FormSwift on April 15, 2020.<ref>{{cite news |last1=St. Amour |first1=Madeleine |title=New Tool for Financial Aid Appeals |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/quicktakes/2020/04/16/new-tool-financial-aid-appeals |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=InsideHigherEd |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hoover |first1=Eric |title=Financial-Aid Appeals Are Mysterious. This Tool Was Built to Simplify Them. |url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Financial-Aid-Appeals-Are/248528 |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=The Chronicle of Higher Eduction |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stratford |first1=Michael |title=New website launches to help college students appeal financial aid decisions |url=https://login.politicopro.com/?redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fsubscriber.politicopro.com%2Farticle%2F2020%2F04%2Fnew-website-launches-to-help-college-students-appeal-financial-aid-decisions-3979337 |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=Politico Pro |date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kreighbaum |first1=Andrew |title=Colleges Brace for Student Aid Appeals as Virus Slashes Incomes |url=https://about.bgov.com/news/colleges-brace-for-student-aid-appeals-as-virus-slashes-incomes/ |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |publisher=Bloomberg Government |date=April 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|https://formswift.com/swift-student/}}\n", "name_user": "A112484011388", "label": "safe", "comment": "added external links to two orgs without wiki entries", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swiftstudent"}
{"title_page": "Midge Ure", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Midge Ure\n| honorific_suffix = {{postnom|country=GBR|size=100|OBE}}\n| image = Midge Ure 2004-10-26.jpg\n| caption = Ure in 2004\n| birth_name = James Ure\n| alias =\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1953|10|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Cambuslang]], [[Lanarkshire]], Scotland\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = {{Flatlist|\n* [[New wave music|New wave]]\n* [[synthpop]]\n* [[post-punk]]\n* [[art rock]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n}}\n| occupation = Musician, singer-songwriter, producer\n| instrument = Vocals, guitar, keyboards, synthesizer\n| years_active = 1972\u2013present\n| associated_acts = [[Slik]], [[Rich Kids]], Misfits, [[Visage (band)|Visage]], [[Thin Lizzy]], [[Ultravox]], [[Band Aid (band)|Band Aid]]\n| website ={{url|midgeure.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''James Ure''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 10 October 1953) better known as '''Midge Ure''', is a Scottish musician, singer-songwriter and producer. His stage name, Midge, is a [[phonetic reversal]] of Jim, the [[diminutive]] form of his actual name.\n\nUre enjoyed particular success in the 1970s and '80s in bands including [[Slik]], [[Thin Lizzy]], [[Rich Kids]] and [[Visage (band)|Visage]], and most notably as frontman of [[Ultravox]]. In 1984, Ure co-wrote and produced the charity single \"[[Do They Know It's Christmas?]]\", which has sold 3.7 million copies in the UK. The song is the second highest selling single in UK chart history.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2012/nov/04/uk-million-selling-singles-full-list |title=UK's million-selling singles: the full list |last=Sedghi |first= Ami |newspaper=The Guardian |location= London |date=4 November 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> Ure co-organised [[Band Aid (band)|Band Aid]], [[Live Aid]] and [[Live 8]] with [[Bob Geldof]]. He acts as a trustee for the charity and also serves as an ambassador for [[Save the Children]].\n\nUre is the producer and writer of several other [[synthpop]]/[[new wave music|new wave]] hit singles of the 1980s, including \"[[Fade to Grey (Visage song)|Fade to Grey]]\" (1980) by Visage and the Ultravox signature songs \"[[Vienna (Ultravox song)|Vienna]]\" (1980) and \"[[Dancing with Tears in My Eyes]]\" (1984).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/4078580.stm |title=Midge Ure: Music's quiet man |work=[[BBC News]] |location= London |date=10 June 2005 |accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> Ure achieved his first UK top 10 solo hit in 1982 with \"[[No Regrets (Tom Rush song)|No Regrets]]\". In 1985, his solo debut album ''[[The Gift (Midge Ure album)|The Gift]]'' reached number two in the [[UK Albums Chart]] and yielded the UK number one single, \"[[If I Was]]\". Ure also co-wrote [[Phil Lynott]]'s \"[[Yellow Pearl (song)|Yellow Pearl]]\", which served as the theme of ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' for much of the 1980s.\n\n==Career==\n===Early years===\nBorn to a working-class family in [[Cambuslang]], Lanarkshire, Scotland, Ure attended [[Rutherglen Academy]] until he was 15 years old. For the first 10 years of his life he lived in a one-bedroom tenement flat in Cambuslang (on the outskirts of Glasgow) with his brother, sister and parents,<ref name=\"mcgrath1\">{{cite news |last=McGrath |first=Nick |title=Midge Ure: My family values |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/sep/22/midge-ure-ultravox-family-values |accessdate=11 February 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=22 September 2012}}</ref> later moving to a new house in nearby [[Eastfield, South Lanarkshire|Eastfield]].<ref>[https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/midge-ure-tells-viewers-love-9596988Midge Ure tells viewers of his love for Cambuslang], Daily Record, 11 January 2017</ref> \n\nAfter leaving school Ure attended Motherwell Technical College and then began to work as an engineer, training at the [[National Engineering Laboratory]] (NEL), in nearby East Kilbride.<ref name=Hanks>{{cite news |last=Hanks |first=Robert |title=Midge Ure: Back in the spotlight |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/midge-ure-back-in-the-spotlight-6144881.html |accessdate=25 July 2012 |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=4 June 2005}}</ref> He started playing music in a Glasgow band called Stumble (c.1969 \u2013 c.1971). The band's line-up included lead guitarist Alan Wright, Fraser Spiers on harmonica, Kenny Ireland on bass and Alec Baird on drums.\n\nUre joined Salvation as a guitarist in 1972. The band had been formed in Glasgow in June 1970 by the brothers [[Kevin McGinlay|Kevin]] (vocals) and [[Jim McGinlay]] (bass guitar). Jim McGinlay (born James McGinlay) decided to turn Ure's name backwards to \"Mij\" (Midge) to avoid any confusion caused by two members of the band having the same first name.<ref name=Hanks /> Ure has since presented himself in the music scene as Midge Ure.<ref name=\"Kevin McGinlay Salvation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kevinmcginlay.com/kevin_early.html |title=Kevin McGinlay Salvation |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226202501/http://www.kevinmcginlay.com/kevin_early.html |archivedate=26 February 2009 }}</ref> The band performed covers as house band in the Glasgow discoth\u00e8que Clouds. The band also comprised [[Billy McIsaac]] on keyboards and [[Kenny Hyslop]] on drums.\n\nIn April 1974, Kevin McGinlay left to pursue a solo career,<ref name=\"Kevin McGinlay Salvation\"/> so Ure assumed vocals in addition to his guitar duties. In November 1974, the band changed its name to [[Slik]], with [[Bay City Rollers]] writers [[Bill Martin (musician)|Bill Martin]] and [[Phil Coulter]] providing songs. In 1975 Ure turned down an offer to be the lead singer of the [[Sex Pistols]], stating that he felt at the time that [[Malcolm McLaren]] had \"his priorities completely wrong!\", a position he later reversed.<ref>\"[http://www.friendsofscotland.gov.uk/scotlandnow/issue-05/arts/midge-ure-interview.html Midge Ure interview]\", Global Friends of Scotland. [https://web.archive.org/web/20090106182548/http://www.friendsofscotland.gov.uk/scotlandnow/issue-05/arts/midge-ure-interview.html Archived] 14 January 2009.</ref>\n\nSlik achieved a UK number one single in February 1976 with \"[[Forever and Ever (Slik song)|Forever and Ever]]\". In early 1977, Jim McGinlay decided to quit the band, being replaced by [[Russell Webb (musician)|Russell Webb]]. Slik terminated their contract with Martin and Coulter, believing that their boy-band image was hindering their chances of success during the rising [[punk rock]] scene. They changed their name to [[PVC2]] and adopted a more punkish style. Ure's only release with the band under this name was the single \"[[Put You in the Picture]]\".\n\n===Rich Kids===\nBy October 1977, Ure had left PVC2 to join former Sex Pistol [[Glen Matlock]] in [[Rich Kids]]. He moved to London and soon found himself immersed in a scene he had previously only read about in the pages of the ''[[NME]]''.<ref name=FOS>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/rockingscots/pip/archive/|title=BBC \u2013 (none) \u2013 Rocking Scots \u2013 Archive|website=Bbc.co.uk}}</ref> Musical tensions within the band led to Ure's departure. Having acquired a Yamaha CS50 synthesiser, Ure \u2013 alongside bandmate [[Rusty Egan]] \u2013 wanted to integrate the new instrument into the band's sound. With Glen Matlock and Steve New preferring to remain with the traditional guitars and drums approach, the band split.\n\nIn January 2010, [[Rich Kids]] reformed, for one night only, for a benefit concert for [[Steve New]] who was fighting terminal cancer (and died on 24 May 2010).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shapersofthe80s.com/2010/05/24/2010-%E2%9E%A4-rich-kid-steve-new-aka-stella-nova-dies-at-50|title=2010 \u27a4 Rich Kid Steve New (aka Stella Nova) dies at 50|date=24 May 2010|publisher=Shapersofthe80s.com|accessdate=17 June 2013}}</ref> Although it had been over 30 years since they played together, the press reports praised the gig, which included energetic performances of \"Ghosts of Princes in Towers\" and \"Hung on You\". [[Rich Kids]] were joined on stage by [[Mick Jones (The Clash)]] and [[Gary Kemp]]. Ure also played an acoustic set of [[Ultravox]] and [[Visage (band)|Visage]] songs.\n\nIn February 2016, it was announced that Rich Kids would reform for a joint headline show with [[The Professionals (band)|The Professionals]] at London's [[O2 Shepherds Bush Empire]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.withguitars.com/rich-kids-professionals-joint-headline-show-announced-first-time-ever/|title=Rich Kids and The Professionals \u2013 Joint Headline Show Announced For The First Time Ever|date=3 February 2016|website=WithGuitars.com}}</ref>\n\n===Visage===\nIn 1978, Egan and Ure formed [[Visage (band)|Visage]] with lead vocalist [[Steve Strange]], and utilised their new synthesiser when they recorded a cover of the Zager & Evans classic \"[[In The Year 2525]]\" for promotional purposes. The line-up was expanded in 1979 with the addition of [[Magazine (band)|Magazine]] members [[Dave Formula]], [[John McGeoch]] and [[Barry Adamson]], and [[Ultravox]] keyboardist [[Billy Currie]], and the band signed briefly to Radar Records for the release of their first single \"[[Tar (song)|Tar]]\". Egan and Ure also formed the short-lived band [[The Misfits (UK band)|The Misfits]], whose career was curtailed by an approach from [[Thin Lizzy]]. Though Visage's first single was unsuccessful, they signed with [[Polydor Records]] in 1980; their second single, \"[[Fade to Grey (Visage song)|Fade to Grey]]\", became a hit.\n\n===Thin Lizzy===\nUre already knew [[Thin Lizzy]] singer [[Phil Lynott]], and in early 1979 Ure received co-writing credit for \"Get Out of Here\" on Thin Lizzy's album ''[[Black Rose: A Rock Legend|Black Rose]]''. In July 1979 Ure stepped in to help Thin Lizzy complete a US tour following guitarist [[Gary Moore]]'s abrupt departure. Ure also contributed guitar parts to \"Things Ain't Working Out\" and \"Dublin\" for the 1979 Thin Lizzy remix compilation ''[[The Continuing Saga of the Ageing Orphans]]''. Thin Lizzy then toured America and Japan. In 1980, during the second part of this tour, Ure switched to keyboards, and was replaced by [[Dave Flett]] and then [[Snowy White]] as guitarist. At the end of the tour Ure left Thin Lizzy and returned to his primary interest at that time, [[Ultravox]]. Ure continued to collaborate with Lynott, co-writing Lynott's biggest solo hit, \"[[Yellow Pearl (song)|Yellow Pearl]]\".\n\n===Ultravox===\nIn 1979, Ure and [[Billy Currie]] formed a close bond playing together in [[Visage (band)|Visage]]. Rusty Egan persuaded Billy Currie to ask Ure if he was interested in joining a revived Ultravox.  Ultravox had been presumed defunct since guitarist [[Robin Simon]] quit and lead singer [[John Foxx]] had left to pursue a solo career. In April 1979 Ure regrouped the band and assumed duties as singer, songwriter, guitarist and second keyboardist. This second incarnation would become the classic line-up, with Currie (keyboards, violin), [[Chris Cross]] (bass) and [[Warren Cann]] (electronic drums). Although Ure had spent the latter half of 1979 on tour with Thin Lizzy, Ultravox found time late in the year to tour in the USA. During this time the band wrote a number of songs which were included on their first album with Ure.\n\nThe album, ''[[Vienna (album)|Vienna]]'', was recorded in 1980. Although it was the band's fourth album, it was the first with Ure, and the first one to chart, although it was only a minor success on first release. However, when the title track \"[[Vienna (Ultravox song)|Vienna]]\" was released as a single in early 1981 it became a huge hit and spent four weeks at no.2 in the UK singles chart and was the 5th highest selling single in the UK that year. The album itself re-entered the album chart and peaked at no.3. Inspired by the 1949 film ''[[The Third Man]]'', the promo video for \"Vienna\" was directed by [[Russell Mulcahy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mvdbase.com/video.php?id=28754|title=Ultravox \u2013 Vienna (version 1: concept)|last=Garcia|first=Alex S|accessdate=26 July 2008|work=Music Video Database|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002075852/http://mvdbase.com/video.php?id=28754|archive-date=2 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> utilising cinematic techniques, and became quite influential. In an interview Ure recalled the way that \"music video changed after that. All these things that became video clich\u00e9s \u2013 cropping the top and bottom off the screen, shooting on film as opposed to videotape, making it look like a movie ... we were quite a groundbreaking act for a while.\"<ref name=FOS /> The same year that Ultravox released the ''Vienna'' album, Visage also released their [[Visage (Visage album)|debut album]] which made the UK Top 20 and featured the hit single \"[[Fade to Grey (Visage song)|Fade to Grey]]\" (co-written by Ure and Currie with [[Dramatis|Chris Payne]]), also influential in the direction of the [[New Romantic]] electropop music scene.<ref>Rimmer, Dave. ''New Romantics: The Look'' (2003), Omnibus Press. {{ISBN|0-7119-9396-3}}</ref>\nFor a while between 1979 and 1980, then, Ure was deeply committed to three different bands, all of them quite successful: Ultravox, Visage and Thin Lizzy.\n\n[[File:Midge April84.JPG|thumb|Ultravox (Midge Ure) in concert, April 1984]]\n\nIn 1981, Ultravox recorded their second album with Ure as frontman, ''[[Rage in Eden]]'', which was a Top 5 hit in the UK. After its release Ure and Currie reconvened with Visage to record the band's second album, ''[[The Anvil (album)|The Anvil]]''. Released in early 1982, it was a Top 10 hit; but Ure left the band soon after its release, citing creative differences with frontman Steve Strange. The same year saw Ultravox record and release their third album with Ure, ''[[Quartet (Ultravox album)|Quartet]]'', with production by [[Beatles]] producer [[George Martin]]. The album became their third Top 10 hit and featured four Top 20 singles. This period saw Ure work as a producer for other artists, amongst them [[Steve Harley]], [[Skids (band)|Skids]] and [[Strasse Music Artist|Strasse]], and in 1982 he released his first solo single, a cover of the 1968 [[Tom Rush]] song \"[[No Regrets (Tom Rush song)|No Regrets]]\" (based on the 1975 hit cover version by [[The Walker Brothers]]), which made the UK Top 10.\n\nAfter the live album ''[[Monument (Ultravox album)|Monument]]'' in 1983 Ultravox released their fourth studio album with Ure, ''[[Lament (Ultravox album)|Lament]]'', in 1984. The album was another Top 10 success and contained the Top 3 hit \"[[Dancing with Tears in My Eyes]]\". The band released their first \"greatest hits\" album at the end of the year, featuring all the singles from 1980 onwards. The album peaked at no.2 in the UK and was later certified triple platinum.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ultravox (albums)|url = http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/18593/ultravox/|website=Officialcharts.com|access-date = 16 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter Ure's successful debut solo album in 1985, the fifth and final Ultravox album with Ure, ''[[U-Vox]]'', was released in 1986. Although another Top 10 hit, the album (and singles) fared less well than their earlier releases.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Ulstravox \u2013 u-vox|url = http://www.officialcharts.com/search/albums/u-vox/|website=Officialcharts.com|access-date = 16 January 2016}}</ref> After the end of the U-Vox Tour Ure left Ultravox. He stated in an Extreme Voice Fanzine 1991: \"The spark kind of went out of it for me, Live Aid and Band Aid had a lot to do with it, I suppose. We had a long break from each other and when we came back together we were all working in different directions\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ultravox.org.uk/cgi-bin/ImageFolio43/imageFolio.cgi?direct=Fanzines%2FExtreme_Voice |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806084958/http://www.ultravox.org.uk/cgi-bin/ImageFolio43/imageFolio.cgi?direct=Fanzines%2FExtreme_Voice |archive-date=6 August 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2009, Ure and the other members (Cann, Currie and Cross) reformed Ultravox for the Return to Eden tour to celebrate the 30th anniversary of the ''Vienna'' album, and in their own words, the \"anniversary of their classic line-up\". Ure stated in a BBC interview in April 2009, \"we are not trying to get our youth back, nor the hair that's fallen off already\".<ref>\"[http://www.indielondon.co.uk/Music-Review/ultravox-announce-uk-dates-for-return-to-eden-tour-2009 Ultravox announce UK dates for Return to Eden tour (2009)]\" ''indieLONDON'', 2008.</ref><ref>Spencer, Kathryn. \"Midge collects another degree\", 27 November 2008, ''[[Daily Express]]''.</ref> After appearing at the Isle of Wight 2009 Festival Ultravox followed up the next year with a second round of the tour. In late 2010, Ultravox started working on their sixth album fronted by Ure. This album, titled ''[[Brilliant (album)|Brilliant]]'', was released in May 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Eames|first=Tom|title=Ultravox release first new album with Midge Ure in 26 years|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a384644/ultravox-release-first-new-album-with-midge-ure-in-26-years.html|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=25 July 2012|date=31 May 2012}}</ref> Following this release the band embarked on the 'Brilliant Tour' performing shows in the UK and Europe in late 2012. In November 2013, Ultravox were special guests on a four-date arena tour with [[Simple Minds]].\n\n===Band Aid and charity work===\nIn 1984, Ure co-wrote the [[Band Aid (band)|Band Aid]] hit, \"[[Do They Know It's Christmas?]]\" with [[Bob Geldof]]. Ure was rehearsing with Ultravox for an episode of the [[Channel 4]] music show \"[[The Tube (TV series)|The Tube]]\" when host [[Paula Yates]] handed him the phone. It was her then husband, Geldof, who proceeded, recalls Ure, \"to rant on about the [[Michael Buerk]] BBC news report on the Ethiopian famine\". Geldof provided the initial lyrics, with Ure working the musical theme on a small keyboard in his kitchen. The second half was composed by Ure, with the bridging chorus only assembled in the studio when the artists had gathered. Ure has described the song as not one of the best he has ever written, commenting that \"the momentum the artists gave it in the recording studio is what made it\".<ref>Crichton, Torcuil. \"Whatever Happened To Midge Ure?\" 25 November 2007, ''[[Sunday Herald]]''</ref>\n\nAt the studio recording Ure took on the production duties for the song. Although [[Trevor Horn]] had been approached to undertake this role, he needed more time to fulfil other obligations than was available.<ref>Hunt, Dennis. \"Pop Music Ure, The Elf Behind 'Christmas'\", 28 April 1985, ''[[LA Times]]'', p.63.</ref> Ure stepped into the breach, with Horn providing his studio, remixing the track and producing the 12\" version. Ure and Geldof jointly set up the [[Band Aid Trust]], and he remains active as a Band Aid Trustee. He also co-organised the [[Live Aid]] concert of 1985 along with Geldof and [[Harvey Goldsmith]]. Geldof and Ure have been honoured with two Ivor Novello awards for writing the song.<ref>\"Live Aid duo win second Ivor gong\", 4 June 2005, ''[[Music Week]]'', p.1</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Ure helped to organise the [[Nelson Mandela 70th Birthday Tribute]], which he also performed at.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/midge-ure-back-in-the-spotlight-492936.html|title=Midge Ure: Back in the spotlight|date=4 June 2005|website=The Independent}}</ref> He has also been the Musical Director and performed at [[The Prince's Trust]] rock concerts in 1982, 1986, 1987, 1988, 2010 and 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/dayandnight/155015/Midge-Ure-Trust-me-Prince-Charles-hated-the-music|title=Midge Ure: Trust me, Prince Charles hated the music|date=30 January 2010|website=Express.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/princes-trust-rock-gala-1987-mw0001199148|title=Prince's Trust Rock Gala 1987 \u2013 Various Artists &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/princes-trust-1986-birthday-party-mw0001204703|title=Prince's Trust: 1986 Birthday Party \u2013 Various Artists &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits|website=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wolfgangs.com/secure/sign-in.html?referrer=cv&return=/music/|title=Referral Program|website=Wolfgangs.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.whereseric.com/eric-clapton-tour/17/11/2010|title=17 November 2010 \u2013 Prince&#039;s Trust Rock Gala with Eric Clapton, others|first=Royal Albert Hall London United|last=Kingdom|website=Where's Eric!}}</ref>\n\nUre performed at [[Music for Montserrat]] on 15 September 1997 to raise funds for the Caribbean island of [[Montserrat]]. It had been devastated by [[Hurricane Hugo]] in 1989 and again in 1997, when the island was impacted by volcanic activity. Ure himself lost a house on Montserrat, which was destroyed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/fameandfortune/10881260/Midge-Ure-Band-Aid-came-at-a-price.html|title=Midge Ure: 'Band Aid came at a price'|first=Nick|last=McGrath|date=8 June 2014|website=Telegraph.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=If I Was...: The Autobiography.|last=|first=|publisher=Virgin Books|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalalberthall.com/about-the-hall/news/2014/october/eric-claptons-most-memorable-royal-albert-hall-moments/|title=Eric Clapton's most memorable Royal Albert Hall moments &#124; Royal Albert Hall|website=Royalalberthall.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 July 1999, Ure was the Musical Director of the Wicked Women concert for the [[Breakthrough Breast Cancer]] charity held at [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]] in London,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/pop-wicked-women-1108300.html|title=independent|last=|first=|date=23 June 1999|website=Independent.co.uk|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref> featuring artists like [[Robbie Williams]] and [[Lisa Stansfield]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lisastansfield.net/tour-history-1990---1999.html|title=Lisa Tours|last=|first=|date=12 February 2018|website=Lisastansfield.net|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/403285.stm|title=bbc|last=|first=|date=25 July 1999|website=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, he organised [[Live 8]] concerts with [[Bob Geldof]] with the aim of pressing [[G8]] leaders into taking action to end world poverty. Later that year he was appointed an Officer of the [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for services to music and charity in the [[2005 Birthday Honours]].<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57665 |date=11 June 2005 |page=13 |supp=y}}</ref> He has received five honorary degrees and was made an Honorary [[Doctor of Arts]] in 2005 by the [[University of Abertay Dundee]] for his artistic and charity work over the past 30 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/4335884.stm|title= Midge Ure given honorary degree |work=BBC News | date=12 October 2005 | accessdate=5 January 2010}}</ref> He was made a [[Doctor of Music]] by [[University of Edinburgh]] in 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://news.scotsman.com/education.cfm?id=313902006|title= Midge Ure in line for great big honour from university, 1&nbsp;March 2006 | location=Edinburgh | newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|first=Joanna|last=Vallely|date=1 March 2006}}</ref> In 2007, he received his third honorary doctorate, from the [[University of Paisley]], for his contribution to Scottish culture and charity work.<ref>{{Cite news|url= http://news.scotsman.com/music.cfm?id=995212007|title= Third degree for Scots singer Midge Ure, 26&nbsp;June 2007 | location=Edinburgh | newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=26 June 2007}}</ref> In 2008, Glasgow Caledonian University awarded him his fourth honorary doctorate, for his musical and humanitarian achievements.<ref>\"Midge tots up 4th uni honour\". 26 November 2008, ''Evening Times''.</ref>\n\nUre was awarded an honorary Doctor of Laws from the [[University of Bath]] in December 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singer Midge Ure to receive honorary degree from University of Bath|url=http://www.thisisbath.co.uk/Singer-Midge-Ure-set-receive-honorary-degree-University-Bath/story-11324665-detail/story.html|accessdate=25 July 2012 |newspaper=[[Bath Chronicle]] |date=7 December 2010}}</ref> As an ambassador for [[Save the Children]], Ure returned to [[Ethiopia]] in 2004<ref name=\"SaveTheChildren Ambassadors\">{{cite web|title=Midge's work with Save the Children|url=http://www.savethechildren.org.uk/about-us/who-we-work-with/artists-and-ambassadors/midge-ure|publisher=Save the Children|accessdate=25 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322091941/http://www.savethechildren.org.uk/about-us/who-we-work-with/artists-and-ambassadors/midge-ure|archivedate=22 March 2012}}</ref> and 2009<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.savethechildren.org.uk/2009/11/always-smiling-and-waving\u2026/ |title=Always smiling and waving |first=Jude |last=Millins |publisher=Save the Children |date=10 November 2009 |accessdate=27 December 2016}}</ref> and visited [[Sierra Leone]] in 2006.<ref name=\"SaveTheChildren Ambassadors\"/>\n\n===Solo career===\n[[File:Midge Ure Here and Now Tour 2011 162 v2.jpg|thumb|right|Midge Ure during Here and Now Tour 2011]]\n\nAfter working on the Band Aid project and during a hiatus from Ultravox, Ure pursued a solo career in 1985. The single, \"[[If I Was]]\", was a UK number one single, and his debut album, ''[[The Gift (Midge Ure album)|The Gift]]'', reached No.&nbsp;2. Ure recruited [[Mick Ronson]] to play guitar on his upcoming solo tour. They rehearsed, but financial disagreements and musical differences put an end to it, and [[Zal Cleminson]] took over in the five-piece band, alongside [[Craig Armstrong (composer)|Craig Armstrong]] on keyboards and [[Kenny Hyslop]] on drums. After returning to Ultravox for what would be their final album together, the band effectively disbanded in 1987 and Ure concentrated solely on his solo career but with less commercial success.\n\nThe second album ''[[Answers to Nothing]]'' (1988) failed to make the UK top 20. It featured a duet with [[Kate Bush]] called \"Sister and Brother\", and the single \"Dear God\", which helped Ure gain his first foothold with American audiences. It reached  #6 on the [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|US Billboard Mainstream Rock chart]] and at #4 on the US [[Alternative Songs|Billboard Alternative Music chart]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicvf.com/song.php?title=Dear+God+by+Midge+Ure&id=28981|title=Dear God (song by Midge Ure) \u2022\u2022\u2022 Music VF, US & UK hits charts|website=Musicvf.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tampabay.com/dear-god-how-could-midge-ure-only-hit-the-charts-once-in-the-us/2271375/|title=Dear God, how could Midge Ure only hit the charts once in the U.S.?|website=Tampa Bay Times}}</ref> The following year Ure toured in the US with [[Howard Jones (musician)|Howard Jones]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=If I Was...: The Autobiography|last=|first=|publisher=Virgin Books|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\nA change of label to [[Arista Records|Arista]]-[[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]] for his third solo album ''[[Pure (Midge Ure album)|Pure]]'' (1991) saw him back in the UK Top 40. It contained the single \"Cold, Cold Heart\" which reached UK Top 20,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/cold,-cold-heart/|title=Official Chart|last=|first=|date=|website=Officialcharts.com|access-date=}}</ref> and \"I See Hope in the Morning Light\", a song written about the possible release of [[Nelson Mandela]] and recorded as a celebration. 11 November 1991, Ure played at the [[Royal Albert Hall]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.midgeure.co.uk/archive/pure.html|title=archive|last=|first=|date=9 August 2018|website=Midgeure.co.uk|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref> with a five-piece band featuring drummer [[Mark Brzezicki]], multi-instrumentalist Willie Dowling and keyboard player [[Josh Phillips (musician)|Josh Phillips]]. From 22 March to 22 April 1992 Ure toured in the U.S. with four songwriters, [[Don Henley]], [[Chip Taylor]], [[Darden Smith]] and [[Rosie Flores]]. The tour was called \"In their own Words\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ultravox.org.uk/cgi-bin/ImageFolio43/imageFolio.cgi?direct=Fanzines/Extreme_Voice|title=Extreme Voice Fanzine|last=|first=|date=21 January 2019|website=Ultravox.org.uk|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1992-04-17-ca-754-story.html|title=On a Road Test : Five Strangers Sing Praises Instead of Blues About Unique Tour Headed for Coach House|date=17 April 1992|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref>\n\n''If I Was'', a retrospective compilation of solo and Ultravox hits, was released in February 1993 by Chrysalis. To support the release he went on a tour in the U.K. called \"Out Alone\" which saw Ure performing on his own, accompanying himself primarily on just an acoustic guitar and a keyboard.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.electricityclub.co.uk/midge-ure-interview/|title=MIDGE URE Interview|website=Electricityclub.co.uk|date=1 June 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> His fourth solo album ''[[Breathe (Midge Ure album)|Breathe]]'' (1996) was produced by [[Richard Feldman (songwriter)|Richard Feldman]]. This album had a very Celtic feel with a plethora of acoustic instruments from Uilleann pipes to mandolins and accordions.  In 1998 the single \"[[Breathe (Midge Ure song)|Breathe]]\" became a hit-single, in several European countries boosted by its use in a [[Swatch]] TV ad campaign, two years after its original release. It entered at #1 both at the Italian and the Austrian charts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://austriancharts.at/showitem.asp?interpret=Midge+Ure&titel=Breathe&cat=s|title=Chart|last=|first=|date=|website=Austriancharts.at|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref> \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0\n\nUre also recorded the soundtrack to the American film, directed by [[Richard Schenkman]], ''[[Went to Coney Island on a Mission from God... Be Back by Five|Went to Coney Island on a Mission from God...be Back by Five]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Midge ure If I Was the autobiography|last=|first=|publisher=Virgin Books|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Midge-Ure-Went-To-Coney-Island-On-A-Mission-From-God-Be-Back-By-Five/release/8916476|title=Midge Ure - Went To Coney Island On A Mission From God... Be Back By Five|website=Discogs.com}}</ref>\n\nUres fifth solo album, ''[[Move Me (Midge Ure album)|Move Me]]'', was first released September 2000, on [[Arista Records|Arista]] label in Germany, later to be released 2001 in the UK on [[Curb Records]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Midge Ure: If I Was The Autobiography|last=|first=|publisher=Virgin Books|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> In March 2001 Ure was a Guest Star in ''[[This Is Your Life (UK TV series)|This is Your Life]]'' on BBC1.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/this-is-your-life-uk/midge-ure-785810/|title=This Is Your Life|last=|first=|date=28 March 2001|website=Tv.com|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.getreading.co.uk/whats-on/music/midge-ure-looks-back-cringes-4277029|title=Getreading|last=|first=|date=16 November 2001|website=Getreading.co.uk|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004 Ure released his autobiography ''If I Was'' through Virgin books.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sixdegreesentertainment.com/midge-ure/4588913850|title=Entertainment|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125141737/http://www.sixdegreesentertainment.com/midge-ure/4588913850|archive-date=25 January 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thisisnotretro.com/interviews/midge-ure-ultravox-interview-2004|title=Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=Thisisnotretro.com|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008 ''10'' was released which contains Ure's own interpretations of songs that influenced him and shaped his songwriting. The album was recorded in a log cabin in Eastern Canada, near Montreal, during the long snow bound winter of 2007 \u2013 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.femail.com.au/midge-ure-rewind-80s-festival-interview.htm|title=rewind 80|last=|first=|date=|website=Femail.com.au|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nUre continues to perform his own songs, along with popular Ultravox songs, in concerts both solo, acoustic and with a band. Ure visited the U.S. in 2013 for a tour and did a number of concerts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cleveland.com/popmusic/2013/01/midge_ure_delivers_a_memorable.html|title=Midge Ure delivers a memorable night of Ultravox and more at Beachland (review)|first=Chuck|last=Yarborough|date=17 January 2013|website=Cleveland.com|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nUre worked in over a decade on the next solo album, ''[[Fragile (Midge Ure album)|Fragile]]'', which was released on 7 July 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chaoscontrol.com/midge-ure-interview-2014/|title=Interview|last=|first=|date=11 August 2014|website=Chaoscontrol.com|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref> The album featured the song \"Dark, Dark Night\", a collaboration with [[Moby]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.electricityclub.co.uk/midge-ure-fragile/|title=Text by Chi Ming Lai|last=|first=|date=|website=Electricityclub.co.uk|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6221431/midge-ure-fragile-album-premiere|title=Interview|last=|first=|date=|website=Billboard.com|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 December 2017, the ''Orchestrated'' album was released. It features orchestrated re-recordings of Ultravox and solo career songs arranged by the composer Ty Unwin, and a new track called \"Ordinary Man\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.midgeure.co.uk/|title=Orchestrated|last=|first=|date=|website=Midgeure.co.uk|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/arts_ents/15704682.midge-ure-my-voice-isnt-as-pure-as-it-was-its-a-little-bit-lower-and-a-bit-raspier/|title=Midge Ure: 'My voice isn\u2019t as pure as it was. It\u2019s a little bit lower and a bit raspier'|website=Heraldscotland.com|accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nUre returned to North America in the summer of 2018 on a co-headline tour with [[Paul Young]], called \"The Soundtrack Of Your Life Tour\".<ref>[https://celebrityaccess.com/2018/06/06/midge-ure-paul-young-announce-co-headlining-tour/] {{dead link|date=September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://glidemagazine.com/210593/midge-ure-of-ultravox-talks-highly-influential-career-current-tour-with-paul-young-interview/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=26 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126114040/https://glidemagazine.com/210593/midge-ure-of-ultravox-talks-highly-influential-career-current-tour-with-paul-young-interview/ |archive-date=26 January 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2019 Ure continued to tour with The Band Electronica (Russell Field, Cole Stacey, Joseph O'Keefe) with \"The 1980 Tour\", during which they perform Ultravox's ''Vienna'' album in full and also include highlights from Visage's self-titled\u00a0debut album.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.udiscovermusic.com/news/midge-ure-ultravox-vienna-1980-tour/|title=udiscovermusic|last=|first=|date=2018-12-10|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nUre lives near [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]].  He has been married twice: to actress and writer [[Annabel Giles]], and to Sheridan Forbes.<ref name=Hanks /> He appeared on the 2007 ''[[Celebrity MasterChef]]'' series, winning his heat and progressing to the final on 15 June, alongside [[Nadia Sawalha]] and [[Craig Revel Horwood]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Sloan|first=Billy|title=Rocker Midge Ure reveals his terror as he goes from Popstar to Operastar|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-interviews/2011/06/05/rocker-midge-ure-reveals-his-terror-as-he-goes-from-popstar-to-operastar-86908-23181653/|accessdate=25 July 2012|newspaper=Daily Record|location=Scotland|date=5 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nUre is a recovering alcoholic, something he discusses in his autobiography ''If I Was''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Egan|first=Sean|title=Midge Ure Feeds His Mind|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/midge-ure-feeds-his-mind-20041116|accessdate=25 July 2012|newspaper=Rolling Stone|date=16 November 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Solo discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Album !! [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<ref name=\"British Hit Singles & Albums\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/19606/midge-ure/|title=Midge Ure {{!}} full Official Chart history|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=5 October 2019}}</ref> !! [[Billboard 200|US]] !! Label !! Catalogue !! Notes\n|-\n| 1985 || ''[[The Gift (Midge Ure album)|The Gift]]'' || 2 || \u2013 || [[Chrysalis Records|Chrysalis]] || 0946 CCD 1508 || \u2013\n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[Answers to Nothing]]'' || 30 || 88 || Chrysalis || CCD 1649 || \u2013\n|-\n| 1991 || ''[[Pure (Midge Ure album)|Pure]]'' || 36 || \u2013 || [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]] || 261,922 || \u2013\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Breathe (Midge Ure album)|Breathe]]'' || 95 || \u2013 || BMG || 74321346292 || \u2013\n|-\n| 200